In JavaScript, there are **multiple ways to create objects**. Below is a **clear, interview‑oriented list** from **most common to advanced**, with **examples and when to use each**.

***

## ✅ 1️⃣ Object Literal (Most Common)

### ✅ Syntax

```js
const user = {
  name: "Raja",
  age: 30,
  greet() {
    console.log("Hello");
  }
};
```

### ✅ Use When

*   Creating simple objects
*   Quick and readable code

✅ **Most widely used method**

***

## ✅ 2️⃣ `new Object()` Constructor

```js
const user = new Object();
user.name = "Raja";
user.age = 30;
```

✅ Works same as object literal  
❌ Less readable, rarely used today

***

## ✅ 3️⃣ Constructor Function

### ✅ Syntax

```js
function User(name, age) {
  this.name = name;
  this.age = age;
}

const user1 = new User("Raja", 30);
const user2 = new User("John", 25);
```

### ✅ Use When

*   Creating **multiple similar objects**
*   Pre‑ES6 class pattern

✅ `new` creates:

*   Empty object
*   Binds `this`
*   Returns the object automatically

***

## ✅ 4️⃣ ES6 Class (Modern & Preferred)

```js
class User {
  constructor(name, age) {
    this.name = name;
    this.age = age;
  }

  greet() {
    console.log("Hello");
  }
}

const user = new User("Raja", 30);
```

### ✅ Use When

*   Object‑oriented programming
*   Clean and maintainable code
*   React class components (older)

✅ Syntactic sugar over constructor functions

***

## ✅ 5️⃣ `Object.create()` (Prototype‑based)

```js
const person = {
  greet() {
    console.log("Hello");
  }
};

const user = Object.create(person);
user.name = "Raja";
```

### ✅ Use When

*   Need **manual prototype control**
*   Creating objects without constructors

✅ No `this` confusion  
✅ Powerful for inheritance

***

## ✅ 6️⃣ Factory Function

```js
function createUser(name, age) {
  return {
    name,
    age,
    greet() {
      console.log("Hello");
    }
  };
}

const user = createUser("Raja", 30);
```

### ✅ Use When

*   Avoiding `new` keyword
*   Functional programming style

✅ Simpler and safer than constructors

***

## ✅ 7️⃣ Singleton Object

```js
const AppConfig = {
  apiUrl: "/api",
  timeout: 5000
};
```

### ✅ Use When

*   Only **one instance** is needed
*   Config, constants, utilities

✅ Common in apps and libraries

***

## ✅ 8️⃣ Using `Object.assign()`

```js
const user = Object.assign({}, { name: "Raja", age: 30 });
```

### ✅ Use When

*   Cloning or merging objects
*   Maintaining immutability

⚠️ Performs shallow copy

***

## ✅ 9️⃣ JSON Object (From API / Storage)

```js
const user = JSON.parse('{"name":"Raja","age":30}');
```

### ✅ Use When

*   Data coming from backend
*   LocalStorage, APIs

***

## ✅ Comparison Summary

| Method               | Recommended | Use Case           |
| -------------------- | ----------- | ------------------ |
| Object literal       | ✅✅✅         | Simple objects     |
| Constructor function | ⚠️          | Legacy code        |
| ES6 class            | ✅✅          | OOP & structure    |
| Factory function     | ✅✅          | Functional style   |
| Object.create        | ✅           | Prototype control  |
| Singleton            | ✅           | Config / constants |

***

## ✅ Interview‑Ready One‑Line Answer

> JavaScript objects can be created using **object literals, constructors, ES6 classes, `Object.create()`, factory functions, and singletons**, each suited to different design needs.

***

## ✅ Most Used in Real Projects

✅ Object literal  
✅ ES6 class  
✅ Factory function  
✅ `Object.create` (advanced use)

